LeetCode 2573 — Find the String with LCP
Difficulty: Hard
Topics: String, Greedy, Dynamic Programming, LCP Matrix

Problem Statement
We define the lcp matrix of any 0-indexed string word of n lowercase English letters as an n x n grid such that lcp[i][j] is equal to the length of the longest common prefix between the substrings word[i..n-1] and word[j..n-1].
Given an n x n matrix lcp, return the alphabetically smallest string word that corresponds to lcp. If there is no such string, return an empty string.
Constraints:

1 <= n == lcp.length == lcp[i].length <= 1000
0 <= lcp[i][j] <= n


Examples
Example 1:
Input:  lcp = [[4,0,2,0],[0,3,0,1],[2,0,2,0],[0,1,0,1]]
Output: "abab"
Two alternating letters. Lexicographically smallest is "abab".
Example 2:
Input:  lcp = [[4,3,2,1],[3,3,2,1],[2,2,2,1],[1,1,1,1]]
Output: "aaaa"
Single distinct letter repeated. Smallest is "aaaa".
Example 3:
Input:  lcp = [[4,3,2,1],[3,3,2,1],[2,2,2,1],[1,1,1,3]]
Output: ""
lcp[3][3] = 3 but word[3..3] has length 1, so LCP can only be 1. Invalid.

Intuition
Phase 1 — Greedily Construct the String
We want the lexicographically smallest string, so we assign letters starting from 'a' and move to 'b', 'c', ... only when forced.
The key observation:

If lcp[i][j] > 0, then word[i] and word[j] must start with the same character, meaning word[i] == word[j].

So the algorithm is:

Scan left to right.
If word[i] is unassigned, give it the next available letter ('a', then 'b', ...).
For every j > i where lcp[i][j] > 0, set word[j] = word[i] (they share a prefix, so same starting char).
If we run out of letters (need more than 26), return "".

This greedy works because assigning the earliest possible letter at each unforced position always produces the lexicographically smallest result.
Phase 2 — Validate the Constructed String
After building word, we must verify the LCP matrix is internally consistent. We use the recurrence:
If word[i] == word[j]:
    lcp[i][j] = lcp[i+1][j+1] + 1    (extends the match one step)

If word[i] != word[j]:
    lcp[i][j] = 0                     (no common prefix)

Base case (i == n-1 or j == n-1):
    lcp[i][j] must be exactly 1 if word[i] == word[j], else 0
We validate bottom-up (from i = n-1 down to 0) so that lcp[i+1][j+1] is always already checked when we process lcp[i][j].
Any mismatch → return "".

Dry Run — Example 1
lcp = [[4,0,2,0],
       [0,3,0,1],
       [2,0,2,0],
       [0,1,0,1]]

Phase 1 — Construction:
  i=0: word[0] unset → word[0]='a', current→'b'
       lcp[0][1]=0, lcp[0][2]=2>0 → word[2]='a'
       lcp[0][3]=0
  i=1: word[1] unset → word[1]='b', current→'c'
       lcp[1][2]=0, lcp[1][3]=1>0 → word[3]='b'
  i=2: word[2]='a' already set → skip
  i=3: word[3]='b' already set → skip

  word = ['a','b','a','b'] = "abab"

Phase 2 — Validation (bottom-up):
  (3,3): word[3]==word[3], i==n-1 → lcp must be 1. lcp[3][3]=1 ✅
  (3,2): word[3]='b' != word[2]='a' → lcp must be 0. lcp[3][2]=0 ✅
  (2,3): word[2]='a' != word[3]='b' → lcp must be 0. lcp[2][3]=0 ✅
  (2,2): word[2]==word[2], i==n-1? No. lcp[2][2] must = lcp[3][3]+1 = 2. lcp[2][2]=2 ✅
  (1,3): word[1]='b'==word[3]='b', j==n-1 → lcp must be 1. lcp[1][3]=1 ✅
  (0,2): word[0]='a'==word[2]='a' → lcp[0][2] must = lcp[1][3]+1 = 2. lcp[0][2]=2 ✅
  ... (all checks pass)

  return "abab" ✅

Time & Space Complexity
StepComplexityPhase 1: Greedy constructionO(n²)Phase 2: Validation (nested loop)O(n²)Total TimeO(n²)SpaceO(n) for the word array

Solution (Java)
javaclass Solution {

    public String findTheString(int[][] lcp) {
        int n = lcp.length;
        char[] word = new char[n];
        char current = 'a';

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (word[i] == 0) {
                if (current > 'z') return "";
                word[i] = current;
                for (int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                    if (lcp[i][j] > 0) word[j] = word[i];
                }
                current++;
            }
        }

        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            for (int j = n - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
                if (word[i] != word[j]) {
                    if (lcp[i][j] != 0) return "";
                } else {
                    if (i == n - 1 || j == n - 1) {
                        if (lcp[i][j] != 1) return "";
                    } else {
                        if (lcp[i][j] != lcp[i + 1][j + 1] + 1) return "";
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return new String(word);
    }
}